[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] In computing (specifically data transmission and data storage), a **block**, sometimes called a **physical record**, is a sequence of bytes or bits, usually containing some whole number of records, having a fixed length; a *block size*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Data thus structured are said to be *blocked*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] The process of putting data into blocks is called *blocking*, while *deblocking* is the process of extracting data from blocks.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Blocked data is normally stored in a data buffer, and read or written a whole block at a time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Blocking reduces the overhead and speeds up the handling of the data stream.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] For some devices, such as magnetic tape and CKD disk devices, blocking reduces the amount of external storage required for the data.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Blocking is almost universally employed when storing data to 9-track magnetic tape, NAND flash memory, and rotating media such as floppy disks, hard disks, and optical discs.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Most file systems are based on a block device, which is a level of abstraction for the hardware responsible for storing and retrieving specified blocks of data, though the block size in file systems may be a multiple of the physical block size.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] This leads to space inefficiency due to internal fragmentation, since file lengths are often not integer multiples of block size, and thus the last block of a file may remain partially empty.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Some newer file systems, such as Btrfs and FreeBSD UFS2, attempt to solve this through techniques called block suballocation and tail merging.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Other file systems such as ZFS support variable block sizes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] Block storage is normally abstracted by a file system or database management system (DBMS) for use by applications and end users.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] The physical or logical volumes accessed via *block I/O* may be devices internal to a server, directly attached via SCSI or Fibre Channel, or distant devices accessed via a storage area network (SAN) using a protocol such as iSCSI, or AoE.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] DBMSes often use their own block I/O for improved performance and recoverability as compared to layering the DBMS on top of a file system.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] On Linux the default block size for most file systems is 4096 bytes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] The stat command part of GNU Core Utilities can be used to check the block size.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] In C++, a block can be read using `std::ifstream` (input file stream).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] In C#, a block can be read with the `FileStream` class.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] In Java, a block can be read using `java.io.FileInputStream`.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] In Python, a block can be read with the `read` method of whatever is implementing `io.IOBase`.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/block-data-storage] In Rust, a block can be read with the `read_exact` method of `std::fs::File`.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A **Fenwick tree** or **binary indexed tree** **(BIT)** is a data structure that stores an array of values and can efficiently compute prefix sums of the values *and* update the values.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] It also supports an efficient rank-search operation for finding the longest prefix whose sum is no more than a specified value.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Its primary use is operating on the cumulative distribution function of a statistical frequency table which is updated often.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This structure was proposed by Boris Ryabko in 1989 with a further modification published in 1992.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] It has subsequently become known under the name Fenwick tree after Peter Fenwick, who described this structure in his 1994 article.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A simple array of values is trivial (constant-time) to update but requires $O(n)$ time to compute a prefix sum or search for a prefix length.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] An array of prefix sums can return a prefix sum in constant time, and search for a prefix length in $O(\log n)$ time, but requires $O(n)$ time to update one of the values.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree allows all three operations to be performed in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This is achieved by representing the values as a tree with $n+1$ nodes where each node in the tree stores the sum of the values from the index of its parent (exclusive) up to the index of the node (inclusive).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The tree itself is implicit and can be stored as an array of n values, with the implicit root node omitted from the array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The tree structure allows the operations of value retrieval, value update, prefix sum, and range sum to be performed using only $O(\log n)$ node accesses.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Given an array of values, it is sometimes desirable to calculate the running total of values up to each index according to some associative binary operation (addition on integers being by far the most common).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees provide a method to query the running total at any index, or prefix sum, while allowing changes to the underlying value array and having all further queries reflect those changes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees are particularly designed to implement adaptive arithmetic coding, which maintains counts of each symbol produced and needs to convert those to the cumulative probability of a symbol less than a given symbol.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Development of operations it supports were primarily motivated by use in that case.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is an implicit tree where nodes are consecutively numbered, and parent-child relationships are determined by arithmetic on the node indexes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] An important function in this index arithmetic is the *least significant set bit*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This is the greatest power of two which divides an index i .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] It can be efficiently computed in two's complement arithmetic as $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} -i$ (where & denotes bitwise AND).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is most easily understood using a one-based array $A[n]$ with n values.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Using half-open interval syntax, let $A(i,j]=\{A[k]\}_{k=i+1}^{j},$ the range from i (exclusive) to j (inclusive).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The corresponding Fenwick array $F[n]$ stores the range sums $\textstyle F[i]=\sum A(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i),i]$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] That is, the sum of $\operatorname {lsb} (i)$ values ending with and including $A[i]$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A fictitious node 0 is used in some descriptions, but is never actually accessed and need not be explicitly stored. $\operatorname {lsb} (0)=\infty ,$ but the value is never actually needed. $F[0]$ may be considered to contain the sum of the empty range $A(0,0]=\{\}$ with value 0.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A "Fenwick tree" is actually *three* implicit trees over the same array: the *interrogation tree* used for translating indexes to prefix sums, the *update* tree used for updating elements, and the *search tree* for translating prefix sums to indexes (rank queries).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The first two are normally walked upwards, while the third is usually walked downwards.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The interrogation tree is defined so that the parent of node i is $i-\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} (i-1)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Each level k of the tree contains nodes with indices corresponding to sums of k distinct powers of 2 (with $k=0$ representing an empty sum 0).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] To find the prefix sum $A[1]+\cdots +A[i]$ , sum the values in i , its parent, its parent's parent, and so on up to (but not including) the root.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] To compute a range sum $A[i]+\cdots +A[j]$ , subtract the prefix sums for $i-1$ and j .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This can be optimized by stopping at their first common ancestor.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] An extreme example is asking for a single entry $A[j]$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] In this case, the common ancestor of j and $i=j-1$ is $j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , so start with $F[j]$ and then, as long as $i\neq j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , subtract $F[i]$ and update `i := i - lsb(i)`.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The update tree is the mirror image of the interrogation tree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The parent of node i is $i+\operatorname {lsb} (i)=(i\mathbin {|} (i-1))+1$ (where | denotes bitwise OR).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This conceptual tree is infinite, but only the part with indexes up to n is stored or used.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Excluding the fictitious nodes with indexes greater than n it will be a forest of disjoint trees, one for each bit set in the binary representation of n .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Here, a node's ancestors are all nodes whose range sums include its own.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] To modify one of the values $A[i]$ , add the change to $F[i]$ , then i 's parent, then its grandparent, and so on, until the index exceeds n .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Unlike the other two trees, the search tree is a binary tree, arranged in an order Knuth calls a "sideways heap".
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Each node is assigned a height equal to the number of trailing zeros in the binary representation of its index, with the parent and children being the numerically closest index(es) of the adjacent height.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Nodes with odd indexes ( $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=1$ ) are leaves.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Nodes with even indexes have the closest two nodes of the next-lowest index as children, $i\pm \operatorname {lsb} (i)/2$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Node i 's parent in the search tree is $(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i))\mathbin {|} (2\cdot \operatorname {lsb} (i))$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Although this tree is potentially infinite, we may define its root to be the highest *existing* node, whose index is the greatest power of 2 less than or equal to n .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] It is possible for a node to have a fictitious parent with an index greater than n yet still have an existing grandparent.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] If the example above applied to a 5-node tree, then node 5 would have a fictitious parent 6, but an existing grandparent 4.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The search tree may be considered a combination of the previous two trees.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A node's left subtree contains all of its descendants in the update tree, while its right subtree contains all of its descendants in the interrogation tree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] A node's parent in the search tree is either its interrogation or update parent (depending on whether the node is a right or left child, respectively), and the other type of parent may be found by multiple upward steps in the search tree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] However, upward traversals in the search tree are uncommon; its primary use is to perform rank queries: given a prefix sum, at what index does it appear?
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This is done by a *downward* traversal through the search tree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] During the traversal, three variables are maintained: The current node's index, the rank being sought in the subtree rooted at the current node, and a "fallback index" to be returned if the rank sought is greater than can be found in the subtree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Initially, the current node is the root, the rank sought is the original query, and the fallback index is a special "overflow" value indicating that the rank is not in the tree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] Each step, either the current node is a fictitious node (index greater than n ), or we must decide if the position sought is to the left or right of the end of the current node.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] If the rank sought is less than the Fenwick array value $F[i]$ for the current node, we must search its left subtree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] If it is greater, search its right subtree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] If it is equal, the direction chosen depends on how you wish to handle searches for sums lying exactly between two nodes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] The function ${\text{lsb}}(n)$ computes the *least significant set bit* of the given n or, equivalently, the largest power of two that is also a divisor of n .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] This function can be simply implemented in code through a bitwise AND operation: `lsb(n) = n & (-n)`, assuming two's complement negation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/fenwick-tree] One naïve algorithm to construct a Fenwick tree consists of initializing the tree with null values and updating each index individually.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Prefix sums are trivial to compute in sequential models of computation, by using the formula *yi* = *y**i* − 1 + *xi* to compute each output value in sequence order.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] However, despite their ease of computation, prefix sums are a useful primitive in certain algorithms such as counting sort, and they form the basis of the **scan** higher-order function in functional programming languages.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Prefix sums have also been much studied in parallel algorithms, both as a test problem to be solved and as a useful primitive to be used as a subroutine in other parallel algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Abstractly, a prefix sum requires only a binary associative operator ⊕, making it useful for many applications from calculating well-separated pair decompositions of points to string processing.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Mathematically, the operation of taking prefix sums can be generalized from finite to infinite sequences; in that context, a prefix sum is known as a partial sum of a series.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Prefix summation or partial summation form linear operators on the vector spaces of finite or infinite sequences; their inverses are finite difference operators.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In functional programming terms, the prefix sum may be generalized to any binary operation (not just the addition operation); the higher order function resulting from this generalization is called a **scan**, and it is closely related to the fold operation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Both the scan and the fold operations apply the given binary operation to the same sequence of values, but differ in that the scan returns the whole sequence of results from the binary operation, whereas the fold returns only the final result.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Programming language and library implementations of scan may be either *inclusive* or *exclusive*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In the latter case, implementations either leave *y*0 undefined or accept a separate "*x*−1" value with which to seed the scan.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Either type of scan can be transformed into the other: an inclusive scan can be transformed into an exclusive scan by shifting the array produced by the scan right by one element and inserting the identity value at the left of the array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Conversely, an exclusive scan be transformed into an inclusive scan by shifting the array produced by the scan left and inserting the sum of the last element of the scan and the last element of the input array at the right of the array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The directive-based OpenMP parallel programming model supports both inclusive and exclusive scan support beginning with Version 5.0.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] There are two key algorithms for computing a prefix sum in parallel.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The first offers a shorter span and more parallelism but is not work-efficient.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The second is work-efficient but requires double the span and offers less parallelism.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In the above, the notation $x_{j}^{i}$ means the value of the *j*th element of array *x* in timestep *i*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] With a single processor this algorithm would run in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] However, if the machine has at least *n* processors to perform the inner loop in parallel, the algorithm as a whole runs in *O*(log *n*) time, the number of iterations of the outer loop.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] A work-efficient parallel prefix sum can be computed by the following steps.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] After the first value, each successive number *yi* is either copied from a position half as far through the w sequence, or is the previous value added to one value in the x sequence.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] If the input sequence has n steps, then the recursion continues to a depth of *O*(log *n*), which is also the bound on the parallel running time of this algorithm.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Each of the preceding algorithms runs in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] However, the former takes exactly log2 *n* steps, while the latter requires 2 log2 *n* − 2 steps.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] For the 16-input examples illustrated, Algorithm 1 is 12-way parallel (49 units of work divided by a span of 4) while Algorithm 2 is only 4-way parallel (26 units of work divided by a span of 6).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] However, Algorithm 2 is work-efficient—it performs only a constant factor (2) of the amount of work required by the sequential algorithm—while Algorithm 1 is work-inefficient—it performs asymptotically more work (a logarithmic factor) than is required sequentially.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Consequently, Algorithm 1 is likely to perform better when abundant parallelism is available, but Algorithm 2 is likely to perform better when parallelism is more limited.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Parallel algorithms for prefix sums can often be generalized to other scan operations on associative binary operations, and they can also be computed efficiently on modern parallel hardware such as a GPU.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The idea of building in hardware a functional unit dedicated to computing multi-parameter prefix-sum was patented by Uzi Vishkin.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Asymptotically this method takes approximately two read operations and one write operation per item.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] An implementation of a parallel prefix sum algorithm, like other parallel algorithms, has to take the parallelization architecture of the platform into account.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] More specifically, multiple algorithms exist which are adapted for platforms working on shared memory as well as algorithms which are well suited for platforms using distributed memory, relying on message passing as the only form of interprocess communication.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The following algorithm assumes a shared memory machine model; all processing elements (PEs) have access to the same memory.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] A version of this algorithm is implemented in the Multi-Core Standard Template Library (MCSTL), a parallel implementation of the C++ standard template library which provides adapted versions for parallel computing of various algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In order to concurrently calculate the prefix sum over n data elements with p processing elements, the data is divided into $p+1$ blocks, each containing ${\frac {n}{p+1}}$ elements (for simplicity we assume that $p+1$ divides n).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Note, that although the algorithm divides the data into $p+1$ blocks, only p processing elements run in parallel at a time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In a first sweep, each PE calculates a local prefix sum for its block.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The last block does not need to be calculated, since these prefix sums are only calculated as offsets to the prefix sums of succeeding blocks and the last block is by definition not succeeded.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The p offsets which are stored in the last position of each block are accumulated in a prefix sum of their own and stored in their succeeding positions.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] For p being a small number, it is faster to do this sequentially, for a large p, this step could be done in parallel as well.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] This time the first block does not have to be processed, since it does not need to account for the offset of a preceding block.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] However, in this sweep the last block is included instead and the prefix sums for each block are calculated taking the prefix sum block offsets calculated in the previous sweep into account.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The Hypercube Prefix Sum Algorithm is well adapted for distributed memory platforms and works with the exchange of messages between the processing elements.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] It assumes to have $p=2^{d}$ processor elements (PEs) participating in the algorithm equal to the number of corners in a d-dimensional hypercube.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Throughout the algorithm, each PE is seen as a corner in a hypothetical hyper cube with knowledge of the total prefix sum σ as well as the prefix sum x of all elements up to itself (according to the ordered indices among the PEs), both in its own hypercube.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In a d-dimensional hyper cube with $2^{d}$ PEs at the corners, the algorithm has to be repeated d times to have the $2^{d}$ zero-dimensional hyper cubes be unified into one d-dimensional hyper cube.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Assuming a duplex communication model where the σ of two adjacent PEs in different hyper cubes can be exchanged in both directions in one communication step, this means $d=\log _{2}p$ communication startups.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The Pipelined Binary Tree Algorithm is another algorithm for distributed memory platforms which is specifically well suited for large message sizes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Like the hypercube algorithm, it assumes a special communication structure.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The processing elements (PEs) are hypothetically arranged in a binary tree (e.g. a Fibonacci Tree) with infix numeration according to their index within the PEs.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Communication on such a tree always occurs between parent and child nodes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The infix numeration ensures that for any given PEj, the indices of all nodes reachable by its left subtree $\color {Blue}{[l\dots j-1]}$ are less than j and the indices $\color {Blue}{[j+1\dots r]}$ of all nodes in the right subtree are greater than j.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The parent's index is greater than any of the indices in PEj's subtree if PEj is a left child and smaller if PEj is a right child.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Note the distinction between subtree-local and total prefix sums.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The points two, three and four can lead to believe they would form a circular dependency, but this is not the case.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Lower level PEs might require the total prefix sum of higher level PEs to calculate their total prefix sum, but higher level PEs only require subtree local prefix sums to calculate their total prefix sum.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The root node as highest level node only requires the local prefix sum of its left subtree to calculate its own prefix sum.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Each PE on the path from PE0 to the root PE only requires the local prefix sum of its left subtree to calculate its own prefix sum, whereas every node on the path from PEp-1 (last PE) to the PEroot requires the total prefix sum of its parent to calculate its own total prefix sum.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Note that the algorithm is run in parallel at each PE and the PEs will block upon receive until their children/parents provide them with packets.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] If the message m of length n can be divided into k packets and the operator ⨁ can be used on each of the corresponding message packets separately, pipelining is possible.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] If the algorithm is used without pipelining, there are always only two levels (the sending PEs and the receiving PEs) of the binary tree at work while all other PEs are waiting.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Assuming a communication startup time of $T_{\mathrm {start} }$ and a bytewise transmission time of $T_{\mathrm {byte} }$ , upward and downward phase are limited to $(2\log _{2}p-2)(T_{\mathrm {start} }+n\cdot T_{\mathrm {byte} })$ in a non pipelined scenario.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The algorithm can further be optimised by making use of full-duplex or telephone model communication and overlapping the upward and the downward phase.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] When a data set may be updated dynamically, it may be stored in a Fenwick tree data structure.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] This structure allows both the lookup of any individual prefix sum value and the modification of any array value in logarithmic time per operation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] However, an earlier 1982 paper presents a data structure called Partial Sums Tree (see Section 5.1) that appears to overlap Fenwick trees; in 1982 the term prefix-sum was not yet as common as it is today.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] For higher-dimensional arrays, the summed area table provides a data structure based on prefix sums for computing sums of arbitrary rectangular subarrays.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] This can be a helpful primitive in image convolution operations.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Counting sort is an integer sorting algorithm that uses the prefix sum of a histogram of key frequencies to calculate the position of each key in the sorted output array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] It runs in linear time for integer keys that are smaller than the number of items, and is frequently used as part of radix sort, a fast algorithm for sorting integers that are less restricted in magnitude.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] An early application of parallel prefix sum algorithms was in the design of binary adders, Boolean circuits that can add two n-bit binary numbers.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In this application, the sequence of carry bits of the addition can be represented as a scan operation on the sequence of pairs of input bits, using the majority function to combine the previous carry with these two bits.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Each bit of the output number can then be found as the exclusive or of two input bits with the corresponding carry bit.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] By using a circuit that performs the operations of the parallel prefix sum algorithm, it is possible to design an adder that uses *O*(*n*) logic gates and *O*(log *n*) time steps.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In the parallel random access machine model of computing, prefix sums can be used to simulate parallel algorithms that assume the ability for multiple processors to access the same memory cell at the same time, on parallel machines that forbid simultaneous access.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In Guy Blelloch's Ph.D. thesis, parallel prefix operations form part of the formalization of the data parallelism model provided by machines such as the Connection Machine.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2 provided a hypercubic network on which the Algorithm 1 above could be implemented, whereas the CM-5 provided a dedicated network to implement Algorithm 2.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The reverse operation, decoding a Gray-coded value x into a binary number, is more complicated, but can be expressed as the prefix sum of the bits of x, where each summation operation within the prefix sum is performed modulo two.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] A prefix sum of this type may be performed efficiently using the bitwise Boolean operations available on modern computers, by computing the exclusive or of x with each of the numbers formed by shifting x to the left by a number of bits that is a power of two.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Parallel prefix (using multiplication as the underlying associative operation) can also be used to build fast algorithms for parallel polynomial interpolation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In particular, it can be used to compute the divided difference coefficients of the Newton form of the interpolation polynomial.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] This prefix based approach can also be used to obtain the generalized divided differences for (confluent) Hermite interpolation as well as for parallel algorithms for Vandermonde systems.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Parallel prefix algorithms can also be used for temporal parallelization of Recursive Bayesian estimation methods, including Bayesian filters, Kalman filters, as well as the corresponding smoothers.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The core idea is that, for example, the solutions to the Bayesian/Kalman filtering problems are written in terms of a suitably defined associative filtering operator such that the prefix "sums" of the filtering operator gives the filtering solution.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] This allows parallel prefix algorithms to be applied to compute the filtering and smoothing solutions.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] A similar idea also works for the parallelization of a class of probabilistic differential equation solvers in the context of Probabilistic numerics.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] In the context of Optimal control, parallel prefix algorithms can be used for parallelization of Bellman equation and Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman equations (HJB equations), including their Linear–quadratic regulator special cases.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Here, the idea is that we can define an associative operator for a combination of conditional value functions (conditioned on the end-point), and the prefix sums of this operator give solutions to the Bellman equations or HJB equations.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Prefix sum is used for load balancing as a low-cost algorithm to distribute the work between multiple processors, where the overriding goal is achieving an equal amount of work on each processor.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] The algorithms uses an array of weights representing the amount of work required for each item.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] After the prefix sum is calculated, the work item i is sent for processing to the processor unit with the number [ ⁠prefixSumValue*i*/ totalWork / numberOfProcessors⁠ ].
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Graphically this corresponds to an operation where the amount of work in each item is represented by the length of a linear segment, all segments are sequentially placed onto a line and the result cut into number of pieces, corresponding to the number of the processors.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Below is a lookup table of quarter squares with the remainder discarded for the digits 0 through 18; this allows for the multiplication of numbers up to 9×9.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] If, for example, you wanted to multiply 9 by 3, you observe that the sum and difference are 12 and 6 respectively.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/prefix-sum] Looking both those values up on the table yields 36 and 9, the difference of which is 27, which is the product of 9 and 3.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] In computer science, a **range minimum query** (**RMQ**) solves the problem of finding the minimal value in a sub-array of an array of comparable objects.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Range minimum queries have several use cases in computer science, such as the lowest common ancestor problem and the longest common prefix problem (LCP).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Given an array *A*[1 … *n*] of n objects taken from a totally ordered set, such as integers, the range minimum query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) =arg min *A*[*k*] (with 1 ≤ *l* ≤ *k* ≤ *r* ≤ *n*) returns the position of the minimal element in the specified sub-array *A*[*l* … *r*].
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] In a typical setting, the array A is static, i.e., elements are not inserted or deleted during a series of queries, and the queries to be answered on-line (i.e., the whole set of queries are not known in advance to the algorithm).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] In this case a suitable preprocessing of the array into a data structure ensures faster query answering.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] A naive solution is to precompute all possible queries, i.e. the minimum of all sub-arrays of A, and store these in an array B such that *B*[*i*, *j*] = min(*A*[*i*…*j*]); then a range min query can be solved in constant time by array lookup in B.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] There are Θ(*n*²) possible queries for a length-n array, and the answers to these can be computed in Θ(*n*²) time by dynamic programming.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] As in the solution above, answering queries in constant time will be achieved by pre-computing results.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] However, the array will store pre-computed range minimum queries not for every range [*i*, *j*], but only for ranges whose size is a power of two.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] There are O(log *n*) such queries for each start position i, so the size of the dynamic programming table B is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] After this pre-computing step, a query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) can now be answered in constant time by splitting it into two separate queries: one is the pre-computed query with range from l to the largest memoized value smaller than r.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] The other is the query of an interval of the same length that has r as its right boundary.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] These intervals may overlap, but since we are trying to compute the minimum rather than, for example, the sum of the numbers in the array, this does not matter.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] The overall result can thus be obtained, after the linearithmic time pre-computing, in constant time: the two queries can be answered in constant time and the only thing left to do is to choose the smaller of the two results.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] This solution does pre-computation in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Its data structures use *O*(*n*) space and its data structures can be used to answer queries in logarithmic time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] The array is first conceptually divided into blocks of size *s* = ⁠log *n*/4⁠.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Then the minimum for each block can be computed in *O*(*n*) time overall and the minima are stored in a new array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] For example, using the array *A* = [0,5,2,5,4,3,1,6,3] and a block size of 3 (for illustrative purposes only) yields the minimum array *A'* = [0,3,1].
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Using the solution above, the sub-queries inside the blocks that are not fully contained in the query still need to be answered in constant time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] There are at most two of those blocks: the block containing l and the block containing r.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Constant time is achieved by storing the Cartesian trees for all the blocks in the array.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] For every such tree, the possible result for all queries need to be stored.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] This comes down to *s*2 or *O*(log2 *n*) entries.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] This means the overall size of the table is *O*(*n*).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] To look up results efficiently, the Cartesian tree (row) corresponding to a specific block must be addressable in constant time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] The solution is to store the results for all trees in an array and find a unique projection from binary trees to integers to address the entries.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] This can be achieved by doing a breadth-first-search through the tree and adding leaf nodes so that every existing node in the Cartesian tree has exactly two children.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] The integer is then generated by representing every inner node as a 0-bit and every leaf as a 1-bit in a bit-word (by traversing the tree in level-order again).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] This leads to a size of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ for every tree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] To enable random access in constant time to any tree, the trees not contained in the original array need to be included as well.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] An array with indices of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ bits length has size 2⁠log *n*/4⁠ = *O*(*n*).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] RMQs are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Several applications can be found in Fischer and Heun (2007).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] RMQs can be used to solve the lowest common ancestor problem and are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] The LCA query LCA*S*(*v*, *w*) of a rooted tree *S* = (*V*, *E*) and two nodes *v*, *w* ∈ *V* returns the deepest node u (which may be v or w) on paths from the root to both w and v.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Gabow, Bentley, and Tarjan (1984) showed that the LCA Problem can be reduced in linear time to the RMQ problem.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] It follows that, like the RMQ problem, the LCA problem can be solved in constant time and linear space.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] In the context of text indexing, RMQs can be used to find the LCP (longest common prefix), where LCP*T*(*i*, *j*) computes the LCP of the suffixes that start at indexes i and j in T.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] To do this we first compute the suffix array A, and the inverse suffix array *A*−1.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] We then compute the LCP array H giving the LCP of adjacent suffixes in A.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/range-minimum-query] Once these data structures are computed, and RMQ preprocessing is complete, the length of the general LCP can be computed in constant time by the formula: LCP(*i*, *j*) = RMQH(*A*-1[*i*] + 1, *A*-1[*j*]), where we assume for simplicity that *A*-1[*i*] + 1 <= *A*-1[*j*] (otherwise swap).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:sqrt-block-buckets/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
